# Conceptual JMeter Test Plan - (This is a simplified representation, actual .jmx is XML)
# JMeter allows you to simulate high loads to analyze performance.

# Test Plan: ALX Auth System Performance Test
#  - User Defined Variables:
#    - host: localhost
#    - port: 8080
#    - users: 100 (Number of concurrent users)
#    - ramp_up_period: 10 (Time in seconds to ramp up users)
#    - loop_count: 5 (Number of times each user will execute the test steps)

#  - Thread Group: Simulate Users
#    - Number of Threads (Users): ${users}
#    - Ramp-up Period (seconds): ${ramp_up_period}
#    - Loop Count: ${loop_count}

#    - HTTP Request Defaults:
#      - Protocol: http
#      - Server Name or IP: ${host}
#      - Port: ${port}

#    - Logic Controller: One Time Login (Performed once per thread)
#      - HTTP Request: Login
#        - Method: POST
#        - Path: /api/v1/auth/authenticate
#        - Body Data (JSON):
#          {
#            "email": "user${__threadNum}@example.com",
#            "password": "password123"
#          }
#        - JSON Extractor: Extract JWT Token (store in 'jwt_token' variable)
#          - Variable Names: jwt_token
#          - JSON Path Expressions: $.token

#    - Loop Controller: Authenticated Operations (Loop N times per thread)
#      - HTTP Header Manager: Add Authorization header
#        - Name: Authorization
#        - Value: Bearer ${jwt_token}

#      - HTTP Request: Get User Profile
#        - Method: GET
#        - Path: /api/v1/users/me
#        - Assertions: JSON Assertion for expected user data

#      - HTTP Request: Update User Profile (e.g., change first name)
#        - Method: PUT
#        - Path: /api/v1/users/me
#        - Body Data (JSON):
#          {
#            "firstname": "UpdatedName${__iterationNum}"
#          }
#        - Assertions: JSON Assertion for updated name

#      - Think Time (e.g., Gaussian Random Timer: 100ms offset, 50ms deviation)

#  - Listeners:
#    - Summary Report (for quick overview)
#    - View Results Tree (for detailed request/response during debugging)
#    - Aggregate Report (for response times, throughput, error rates)
#    - Graph Results (for visualizing trends over time)

#  - Pre-requisites:
#    - Ensure test users are pre-registered in the database (e.g., user1@example.com, user2@example.com, etc.)
#      for robust login simulation. This can be done via Flyway seed data or a separate setup script.
#    - Docker Compose setup must be running.

#  - Execution:
#    - Start the Spring Boot application via `docker-compose up`
#    - Open JMeter GUI, load this .jmx plan.
#    - Run the test.
#    - Analyze results in the listeners.